      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1602">
               <p>Like his brother <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1599.xml"
                  />Charles</persName>, Edward (often called &apos;Ned&apos; or &apos;Ted&apos; by
                  the Wesley brothers) was traveling with the Wesley brothers (esp. <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>) soon after his family aligned
                  with the Methodists in <date when="1746">1746</date>. He continued to <seg
                     ana="itinerancy">itinerate</seg> even after marrying <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1601.xml"/>Duriah (&apos;Dudie&apos;) Clarke</persName>
                  (d. <date when="1792">1792</date>) on <date when="1748-09-10">Sept. 10,
                     1748</date> (with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
                  officiating). But Edward and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1599.xml"
                     />Charles</persName> began to chafe at <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s authority in assigning
                  circuits, and by <date when="1755">1755</date> they both claimed the right to
                  administer sacraments (although not ordained). In <date when="1756">1756</date>
                  Edward published <hi rend="italic">The Mitre</hi>, a ferocious poetic attack on
                  the Church of <placeName>England</placeName>, which led to a final break between
                  the Wesley brothers and the Perronet brothers in ministry (if not in affection).
                  It also severely strained Edward&apos;s relationships with his parents. He
                  eventually settled at <placeName>Canterbury</placeName> as an Independent
                  minister, and is best known for his hymn, &apos;All hail the power of Jesus&apos;
                  name&apos;. See Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 335–36; Batty, <hi
                     rend="italic">Perronet</hi>; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 876; <hi rend="italic"
                     >ODNB</hi>; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 270.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
